    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#inglese2011"/>, pp. <citedRange>273-281</citedRange> and fig. 15</bibl>, whence
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>61.1556</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>116100</citedRange></bibl>.
                Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#inglese2013"/>, pp. <citedRange>238-239</citedRange> and fig. 18 p. <citedRange>436</citedRange></bibl>, whence
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>63.1718</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#rosamilia2023"/>, p. <citedRange>49</citedRange>, footnote 27</bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Ἁγήτωρ">Ἁγέ̄τōρ</name></persName> <w>καλός</w>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Hagètôr <supplied reason="subaudible">est</supplied> beau !</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Hagetor <supplied reason="subaudible">is</supplied> fine!</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Hagetor <supplied reason="subaudible">è</supplied> bello!</p>
         </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
                <p>أغيتور (يكون) فاضلًا (جيدًا أونبيلًا).</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                
                <p>This is an acclamation of a type more often preserved on vases than on monuments. However, the lettering leaves no doubt that it is a
                graffito and no official mention.</p>
                <p>The name <foreign xml:lang="grc">Ἁγήτωρ</foreign> is attested for a military officer about 335 BC (<ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr084000</ref>), who
                might be a grand-son or another related person.</p>
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#rosamilia2023"/></bibl> was right in suggesting that the date is plausibly more ancient than the 'end of the fifth or very first years of the fourth century BC' proposed by 
                <bibl><ptr target="#inglese2013"/></bibl>.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
